@article{Brown2002,
abstract = {North American desert rodents have long been a model system for the$\backslash$nstudy of community structure and dynamics. Field experiments and$\backslash$nnonmanipulative observations have provided consistent evidence that$\backslash$ninterspecific competition influences spatial patterns and dynamic$\backslash$nprocesses of community organization. Some of the evidence comes from$\backslash$nassembly rules, which document how the species that coexist in local$\backslash$ncommunities differ in body size, trophic morphology, functional group,$\backslash$nor taxonomy more than would be expected had they been assembled by$\backslash$nsome random process (Kelt and Brown 1999). One assembly rule proposed$\backslash$nby Fox (1987; see also Fox and Brown 1993; Fox 1999; Kelt et al.$\backslash$n1999) is based on functional groups. It hypothesizes that species$\backslash$nare assembled in such a way that each functional group tends to be$\backslash$nfilled before an additional species is added to an existing functional$\backslash$ngroup. Communities that conform to the rule are termed "favored states,"$\backslash$nwhereas other combinations are termed "unfavored states." So if the$\backslash$nrule is operating, we should observe more favored states than expected$\backslash$nby chance. Although Fox's assembly rule has been applied to a variety$\backslash$nof systems (1999), its application to desert rodent communities has$\backslash$ngenerated controversy. Fox and Brown (1993) showed that there were$\backslash$nmore favored states than expected by chance in two large data sets:$\backslash$na sample of 115 communities from the Nevada test site (Jorgensen$\backslash$nand Hayward 1965) and another sample of 201 communities from sites$\backslash$nwidely distributed across the southwestern United States (Brown and$\backslash$nKurzius 1987). Stone et al. (1996; also Simberloff et al. 1999) criticized$\backslash$nFox and Brown, claiming that the apparent conformity to the assembly$\backslash$nrule was an "artifact" of "the fact that the few widespread species$\backslash$nare not treated realistically" (Stone et al. 1996, p. 997). They$\backslash$nfocused on the southwestern data set and argued that the nonrandom$\backslash$npattern of coexistence was due entirely to the sizes and overlaps$\backslash$nof geographic ranges of different species. Kelt and Brown (1999)$\backslash$nand Brown et al. (2000) showed that this was not true. They determined$\backslash$nthe regional species pool for each sample site, composed of just$\backslash$nthose species whose geographic ranges overlapped the site, and then$\backslash$nassembled null communities by drawing the observed number of species$\backslash$nat random from these geographically constrained pools. Their analysis$\backslash$nshowed that the communities obeyed Fox's assembly rule: the observed$\backslash$nassemblages exhibited significantly more favored states than the$\backslash$nrandom draws from the regional pools. Stone et al. (2000) apparently$\backslash$naccepted this result, because in this most recent critique they barely$\backslash$nreferred to the influence of geographic ranges on the patterns of$\backslash$ncoexistence in the southwestern data set. Instead, Stone et al. (2000)$\backslash$nshifted fromthe geographical to the regional scale. They focused$\backslash$non the Nevada data set, where the restricted area insured that all$\backslash$nof the 115 sample sites were within the geographic ranges of the$\backslash$nsame species. They also shifted their argument, suggesting that the$\backslash$nnonrandom patterns of local coexistence are "an artifact of the fact$\backslash$nthat the assembly rule treated all species as equally likely to be$\backslash$nfound on all sites" (Stone et al. 2000, p. 323). They supported this$\backslash$nclaim by performing two analyses of the Nevada data set.},
