@article{Ives1985,
abstract = {Atkinson {\&} Shorrocks (1981) have studied a model for two species compet- ing for use of a patchy and ephemeral resource, and have shown that coexistence can be much easier if the eggs or larvae of each species are distributed in a clumped way (rather than independently randomly) among patches; these authors presented numerical studies in which the competi- tion within and between species in anyone patch was of "contest" form. In this paper we do two things. First, we extend Atkinson {\&} Shorrocks' conclusion by giving analytic results both for "contest" and for the opposite extreme of "scramble" competition within patches; Atkinson {\&} Shorrocks' results are found to be very robust, with the essential features being largely unaffected by the detailed nature of the competition process. Second, we show more generally that any mechanism producing intraspecific aggrega- tion of eggs in a patchy environment is likely to promote coexistence of competing species. In particular, if each female produces a large number of eggs and thence larvae in a single, ephemeral patch (as many insects do), the model's requirement of intraspecific aggregation with no covari- ance between species will tend to be fulfilled. This basic theme-that patterns of aggregative behaviour within a patchy and ephemeral environ- ment may facilitate competitive coexistence-resonates with a lot of broadly similar recent work on the dynamics of predator-prey and para- site-host systems.},
